    "\n",
    "Key Aspects of Pearson’s Correlation:\n",
    "Linearity Only: It only detects straight-line trends. If a relationship is curved (e.g., U-shaped), Pearson's might be zero even if a strong relationship exists.\n",
    "\n",
    "While $R^2$ tells you \"How much,\" the Correlation Coefficient ($r$) tells you \"Which Direction\" and \"How Strong.\" It ranges from -1 to +1.\n",
    "\n",
    "Positive Correlation($+1$): As Distance increases, Density increases (Unlikely for cities).\n",
    "\n",
    "Negative Correlation($-1$): As Distance increases, Density decreases (The \"Standard\" Urban Decay).\n",
    "\n",
    "Near Zero Correlation($0$): No linear relationship."
   ]
